|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/28/0428236           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Stony Stevenson writes "In an effort to inject Microsoft's latest slogan,
'People-ready business', into popular usage (and no doubt raise its
Google page rank), Microsoft asked a passel of A List Bloggers to write
[0]blurbs on what this meaningless phrase means to them. Michael
Arrington, Om Malik, Fred Wilson, Richard MacManus and a handful of
others happily agreed to churn out some mush for Microsoft, which it
later used in banner ads. What it really meant to these guys was income.
Redmond paid the bloggers for every user who clicked through to the PRB
microsite. That caused other bloggers, lead by Gawker chief Nick Denton,
to rightfully question their ethics. [1]A spitball war has been raging
ever since."

