+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| No OLPCs for Cuba, Ever                                            |
|   from the can't-export-that dept.                                 |
|   posted by kdawson on Thursday June 28, @11:24 (Education)        |
|   http://linux.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/28/1357209        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "In a move going largely unnoticed by
developers, the OLPC project now [0]requires all submissions to be hosted
in the RedHat Fedora project. While this may not seem like a big deal,
the implications are interesting. First, contributors have to sign the
[1]Fedora Project Individual Contributor License Agreement. By being
forced to submit contributions to the Fedora repository they
automatically fall under the [2]provisions of US export law. So, no OLPC
for Cuba, Syria and the like. Ever."

Discuss this story at:
    http://linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/28/1357209

Links:
    0. http://lists.laptop.org/pipermail/sugar/2007-June/002709.html
    1. http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Legal/Licenses/CLA
    2. http://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Legal/Export


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Major Flaw Found In Security Products                              |
|   from the deploy-the-captchas dept.                               |
|   posted by kdawson on Thursday June 28, @12:11 (Security)         |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/28/1427228           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

ancientribe writes "A stealthy and potentially dangerous [0]bug has been
discovered in security products from eight different vendors, including
Check Point Software, according to an article in Dark Reading. The
so-called cross-site request forgery (CSRF) lets an attacker access the
user's network and even conduct transactions on behalf of the user. It
could affect over a million installations, but so far, Check Point is the
only security vendor to step up and patch it. This vulnerability is found
in most everything with a Web-based interface, including printers,
firewalls, DSL routers, and IP phones." An article on the vulnerability
from last fall quotes Jeremiah Grossman, CTO of WhiteHat Security, who
[1]calls CSRF "the sleeping giant" vulnerability: "It's not seen as a
vulnerability because it works like the Web works."

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/28/1427228

Links:
    0. http://www.darkreading.com/document.asp?doc_id=127731&WT.svl=news1_1
    1. http://www.darkreading.com/document.asp?doc_id=107651


