[0]Steve Kerrison writes "The Radeon 'R600' HD 2900 XT was late coming,
and so by extension are the lower cost parts derived from it. The Radeon
HD 2400 and 2600s are now available, just the same, with pricing aimed at
knocking mid-range GeForce 8 series cards off people's shopping lists.
There's more to a graphics card than price; performance and driver
functionality are key too. [1]HEXUS had some fun and games testing the
new Radeons: 'The hardware designers may now be sitting back, content
that their DX10-supporting midrange SKUs are at least as compelling as
the competition's. But, and it's a big, big but, the current drivers
aren't realizing the kind of performance we'd expect from a knowledge of
the Radeon HD 2600 XT's setup.'" A very useful article ... unfortunately
spread across a dozen pages with no 'print view' available.

