[0]Riding with Robots writes "After months of scoping out the terrain,
the robotic geologist [1]Opportunity is ready to drive down into Victoria
Crater on the Meridiani Plains of Mars. Mission managers acknowledge the
hardy rover may never come back out, but say they think the potential for
discovery is worth it. 'The rover has operated more than 12 times longer
than its originally intended 90 days. The scientific allure is the chance
to examine and investigate the compositions and textures of exposed
materials in the crater's depths for clues about ancient, wet
environments. As the rover travels farther down the slope, it will be
able to examine increasingly older rocks in the exposed walls of the
crater. '"

